style='font-size:12.0pt'>            &lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class=MsoNormal style='margin-right:-.5in;text-align:justify'>&lt;span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>Limitations of science&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class=MsoNormal style='margin-right:-.5in;text-align:justify'>&lt;span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p class=MsoNormal style='margin-right:-.5in;text-align:justify'>&lt;span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>            Science has three major limitations. First,
&lt;b>(1)&lt;/b> &lt;u>science cannot deal with universals&lt;/u>, or absolutes. It is
subject to “the plague of particularity” because it is limited to the inductive
approach. Science can form and test hypotheses, which are mental deductions
from previous particulars; but these hypotheses are approximate, since they are
based on limited previous experience. Since science cannot deal with the
absolutes of universal space or eternal time, science cannot lead to an
adequate understanding of “the big picture.” In short, science cannot produce a
worldview. It deals more with particulars than with systematics.&lt;/span>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>LANGUAGE, EXEGESIS, AND THEOLOGY</title><link>https://christir.org/essays/ministry/preparation-for-ministry/language-exegesis-and-theology/</link><pubDate>Mon, 16 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://christir.org/essays/ministry/preparation-for-ministry/language-exegesis-and-theology/</guid><description>&lt;style>
